Cell division based metastatic spread One of the hallmarks of cancer is the capability of tumour cells to overcome hostile microenvironments when invading new systems (Hanahan 2011). Therefore, tumour cells need to be highly mutated to survive and establish a successful metastasis, which suggests a proportional relation of the rate of metastasis spread to the average number of mutations in the cancer cells and the rate of cancer cell division. Assuming a constant rate of mutation during cell division such a model has been proposed in Gasparini and Humphreys (2022) as an alternative to the volume based model intensity function (5). It is initially based on the model for lymph node spread by Isheden et al. (2019), where they describe the volume of a spherical, dense tumour without cell death through the number of cell divisions A(t) and the size of a single cell \documentclass[12pt]{minimal}
